<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate baseboard for a room?", answer: "Measure the perimeter of the room in feet — 2 × (length + width) for a rectangle — then subtract 3 feet for each doorway (standard door width). Add 10 percent for cutting waste and miter errors. A 12 × 15 foot room with 2 doors needs 2×(12+15) − 2×3 = 48 linear feet before waste, or ~53 feet with waste. At 8 foot stick length, that's 7 sticks." },
  { question: "How much baseboard per stick?", answer: "Baseboard and trim are sold in sticks (straight lengths) of 8, 10, 12, 14, or 16 feet. 8 foot is most common at big-box stores; 16 foot is standard at lumberyards and is usually better quality. Longer sticks mean fewer joints and less waste — prefer them when your vehicle and installation area allow. Pre-primed MDF is cheapest; solid pine is better for stained finishes." },
  { question: "Do I need extra for cutting waste?", answer: "Yes. 10 percent is standard for a rectangular room with typical door count. Add 15 percent if the room has many corners, alcoves, bay windows, or curved walls — every additional inside/outside corner eats another 4 to 8 inches to miters. For stained baseboard where you cannot cover mistakes with caulk, go 15 percent minimum." },
  { question: "Should I deduct for cabinets and built-ins?", answer: "Yes, if they sit on the floor. Measure the wall length behind built-ins, base cabinets, and full-height pieces and subtract those from the perimeter. Do not deduct for freestanding furniture, which can move. Closet interiors are usually baseboarded, so include those walls in your perimeter." },
  { question: "What does baseboard cost?", answer: "Pre-primed MDF baseboard runs 0.70 to 1.50 dollars per linear foot at big-box stores. Pre-primed pine is 1 to 2 dollars per linear foot. Hardwood like oak or cherry runs 3 to 8 dollars per linear foot. For a typical 12×15 room needing 53 linear feet, budget 40 to 80 dollars for MDF, 60 to 120 dollars for pine, or 160 to 420 dollars for hardwood. Installation adds 1 to 3 dollars per linear foot if you hire it out." }
]) %>

