    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How Baseboard Measurements Work</h2>
      <p>
        Baseboard wraps the perimeter of a room minus door openings. The formula is simple: perimeter = 2 × (length + width), then subtract the combined width of all doorways (usually 3 feet each for interior doors). Add waste for cuts, miter mistakes, and corner kerfs. The calculator handles all three steps and shows the number of sticks needed at your chosen stick length, typically 8, 12, or 16 feet.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Choosing Baseboard Height and Style</h2>
      <p>
        Baseboard height is traditionally proportional to ceiling height: 8 foot ceilings look best with 3 to 5 inch baseboard, 9 foot ceilings with 5 to 7 inch, and 10+ foot ceilings with 7 to 9 inch. Styles include simple colonial, more formal ogee, craftsman flat, and shaker. Pre-primed MDF is the cheapest option and takes paint well. Pre-primed finger-joint pine is slightly more expensive but lighter and less prone to swelling in humid rooms. Solid hardwood is required for stained finishes.
      </p>

      <h2>Installing Baseboard</h2>
      <p>
        The hardest part of baseboard installation is coping inside corners: instead of mitering both sides of an inside corner (which opens up if the walls are out of square), you cut the first piece square against one wall and cope the second piece to fit its profile. Outside corners are 45 degree miters. Use a coping saw, a miter saw, and a nail gun for efficiency. Caulk the top edge to hide gaps against the wall, and fill nail holes with paintable putty before the final coat. Allow MDF to acclimate to the room for 24 hours before installing to prevent later swelling.
      </p>

      <h2>Waste Factor Rules of Thumb</h2>
      <p>
        A rectangular room with 1 to 2 doors uses about 5 percent waste, but use 10 percent for safety. A room with 4 or more corners adds roughly 4 inches per corner for miter cut-offs. Patterned or pre-finished baseboard (oak veneer, stained solid wood) needs 15 percent because you cannot hide mistakes with caulk and paint. Stairs are the worst case — plan 20 to 25 percent waste for skirtboard runs because angled cuts at each step waste a lot.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What's the standard baseboard height?</h3>
      <p>3 to 5 inches for most 8 foot ceilings; taller ceilings take taller baseboard.</p>

      <h3>Pine vs MDF baseboard?</h3>
      <p>MDF is cheaper and paints better; pine is lighter and handles humidity better. Both are fine painted white.</p>

      <h3>Should I caulk baseboard?</h3>
      <p>Yes — caulk the top edge against the wall with paintable latex caulk for a seamless look.</p>

      <h3>How many nails per linear foot?</h3>
      <p>One nail every 16 inches into studs, two per stud — into the top and bottom of the profile.</p>

      <h3>Do I install before or after flooring?</h3>
      <p>Usually after. Flooring tucks under the baseboard bottom, leaving a clean expansion gap hidden by the trim.</p>

